  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
  | character above.)

  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics$
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most$
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and$
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from$
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to$
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary$
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.$
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.$

cat/test_cat/out8.txt


his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

    1	This textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
     2	and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
     3	books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
     4	then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
     5	various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
     6	introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
     7	applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
     8	We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

cat/test_cat/out11.txt


    1	This textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
     2	and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
     3	books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
     4	then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
     5	various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
     6	introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
     7	applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
     8	We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.
     9

   117	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
   118	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
   119	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

  M-NM-5M-aM-<M-0M-OM-^B M-OM-^DM-NM-?M-aM-?M-&M-OM-^DM-NM-? M-OM-^@M-OM-^AM-NM-?M-aM-=M-5M-NM-:M-NM-?M-NM-=M-OM-^DM-NM-1,  M-aM-=M-%M-OM-^CM-NM-8M-aM->M-? Runes:$
$
  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$
$
  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$
$

    68	  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
    69	  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
    70	  | character above.)

    71	Ethiopian:

    93	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
    94	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

    68	  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
    69	  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
    70	  | character above.)

    71	Ethiopian:

    93	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
    94	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

    68	  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled$
    69	  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the$

    92	  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$

    93	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
    94	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$

   116	
   117	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
   118	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
   119	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

   116	
   117	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
   118	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
   119	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

   117	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
   118	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
   119	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$

Thai (UCS Level 2):

  Excerpt from a poetry on The Romance of The Three Kingdoms (a Chinese
  classic 'San Gua'):

  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
  | character above.)

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

Thai (UCS Level 2):

  Excerpt from a poetry on The Romance of The Three Kingdoms (a Chinese
  classic 'San Gua'):

  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
  | character above.)

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

  M-NM-5M-aM-<M-0M-OM-^B M-OM-^DM-NM-?M-aM-?M-&M-OM-^DM-NM-? M-OM-^@M-OM-^AM-NM-?M-aM-=M-5M-NM-:M-NM-?M-NM-=M-OM-^DM-NM-1,  M-aM-=M-%M-OM-^CM-NM-8M-aM->M-?   M-OM-^DM-NM-9M-NM-<M-OM-^IM-OM-^AM-aM-=M-5M-OM-^CM-NM-1M-OM-^CM-NM-8M-NM-1M-NM-9, M-NM-:M-NM-1M-aM-=M-6 M-NM-<M-aM-=M-1M-NM-;M-aM->M-?   M-NM-3M-aM-=M-3M-NM-3M-NM-?M-NM-=M-NM-5M-NM-= M-OM-^DM-NM-1M-aM-?M-&M-OM-^DM-aM->M-?   M-OM-^@M-OM-^AM-NM-?M-NM-;M-NM-1M-NM-2M-NM-5M-aM-?M-^VM-NM-= M-aM-<M-!M-NM-<M-aM-?M-^VM-NM-= M-NM-5M-aM-<M-6M-NM-=M-NM-1M-NM-9 M-OM-^DM-aM-=M-4M-NM-= M-OM-^@M-OM-^AM-aM-=M-=M-OM-^DM-NM-7M-NM-=, M-aM-=M-^EM-OM-^@M-OM-^IM-OM-^B M-OM-^DM-NM-?M-aM-=M-:M-OM-^B M-OM-^CM-OM-^EM-NM-<M-NM-<M-aM-=M-1M-OM-^GM-NM-?M-OM-^EM-OM-^B$
  M-OM-^CM-aM-=M-=M-OM-^CM-NM-?M-NM-<M-NM-5M-NM-=. M-aM-<M-^PM-aM-=M-0M-NM-= M-NM-3M-aM-=M-0M-OM-^A M-OM-^DM-NM-?M-aM-?M-&M-OM-^DM-NM-? Runes:$
$
  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$
$
  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$
$

Thai (UCS Level 2):

  Excerpt from a poetry on The Romance of The Three Kingdoms (a Chinese
  classic 'San Gua'):

  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
  | character above.)

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

  M-NM-5M-aM-<M-0M-OM-^B M-OM-^DM-NM-?M-aM-?M-&M-OM-^DM-NM-? M-OM-^@M-OM-^AM-NM-?M-aM-=M-5M-NM-:M-NM-?M-NM-=M-OM-^DM-NM-1,  M-aM-=M-%M-OM-^CM-NM-8M-aM->M-? Runes:$
$
  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$
$
  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$
$

    68	  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled$
    69	  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the$

    92	  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$

    93	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
    94	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$

Runes:$
$
  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$
$
  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$
$

Thai (UCS Level 2):

  Excerpt from a poetry on The Romance of The Three Kingdoms (a Chinese
  classic 'San Gua'):

  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
  | character above.)

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

  From a speech of Demosthenes in the 4th century BC:

  ÎŸá½Ï‡á½¶ Ï„Î±á½Ï„á½° Ï€Î±Ïá½·ÏƒÏ„Î±Ï„Î±á½· Î¼Î¿Î¹ Î³Î¹Î³Î½á½½ÏƒÎºÎµÎ¹Î½, á½¦ á¼„Î½Î´ÏÎµÏ‚ á¾¿Î‘Î¸Î·Î½Î±á¿–Î¿Î¹,

  áš»á›– áš³áš¹áš«áš¦ áš¦áš«á› áš»á›– á›’áš¢á›žá›– áš©áš¾ áš¦áš«á›— á›šášªáš¾á›žá›– áš¾áš©áš±áš¦áš¹á›–ášªáš±á›žáš¢á›— áš¹á›áš¦ áš¦ášª áš¹á›–á›¥áš«

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics$
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most$
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and$
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from$
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to$
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary$
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.$
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.$

cat/test_cat/out37.txt


    1	This textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
     2	and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
     3	books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
     4	then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
     5	various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
     6	introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
     7	applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
     8	We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

    93	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
    94	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

cat/test_cat/out40.txt


31	In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
   132	data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.



   133	Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
   134	study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its

   135	ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
   136	information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to

   137	decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a



   138	CAT
   139	systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
   140	the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
   141	the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random


   142	outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
   143	decisions on the basis of data. textbook
   144	Statistical
   145	methods are
   146	used in almost every
   147	discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
   148	biology, business, communications, economics,
   149	        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
   150	    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
   151	        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
   152	intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
   153	        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
   154	prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
   155	        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
   156	in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
   157	summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
   158	methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of


   159	statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
   160	data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
   161	whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
   162	steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
   163	statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
   164	properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
   165	question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
   166	proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.

   174	ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into

   185	
   186	
   187	outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
   188	decisions on the basis of data. textbook
   189	Statistical
   190	methods are
   191	used in almost every
   192	discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
   193	biology, business, communications, economics,
   194	        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
   195	    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
   196	        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
   197	intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
   198	        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
   199	prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
   200	        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
   201	in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
   202	summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
   203	methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of
   204	
   205	
   206	statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
   207	data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
   208	whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
   209	steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
   210	statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
   211	properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
   212	question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
   213	proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.
   214	123			11 /_______________________________________________/\0
   215	124 Statistical
   216	methods are
   217	
   218	
   219	used in almost every
   220	discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
   221	
   222	
   223	 		Qbiology, business, communications, economics,

  classic 'San Gua'):

  (The above is a two-column text. If combining characters are handled
  correctly, the lines of the second column should be aligned with the
  | character above.)

  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

  M-bM-^UM-^ZM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-)M-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^]  M-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^X  M-bM-^UM-0M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-/  M-bM-^UM-0M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-/  M-bM-^TM-^WM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-;M-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^[           M-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^UM-^LM-bM-^UM-^LM-bM-^TM-^X M-bM-^UM-^N M-bM-^TM-^WM-bM-^UM-^MM-bM-^UM-^MM-bM-^TM-^[ M-bM-^TM-^K  M-bM-^VM-^AM-bM-^VM-^BM-bM-^VM-^CM-bM-^VM-^DM-bM-^VM-^EM-bM-^VM-^FM-bM-^VM-^GM-bM-^VM-^H
In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.



Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its

ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to

decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a



CAT
systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random


outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
decisions on the basis of data. textbook
Statistical
methods are
used in almost every
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
biology, business, communications, economics,
        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of


statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.

  From a speech of Demosthenes in the 4th century BC:

  M-NM-^_M-aM-=M-^PM-OM-^GM-aM-=M-6 M-OM-^DM-NM-1M-aM-=M-^PM-OM-^DM-aM-=M-0 M-OM-^@M-NM-1M-OM-^AM-aM-=M-7M-OM-^CM-OM-^DM-NM-1M-OM-^DM-NM-1M-aM-=M-7 M-NM-<M-NM-?M-NM-9 M-NM-3M-NM-9M-NM-3M-NM-=M-aM-=M-=M-OM-^CM-NM-:M-NM-5M-NM-9M-NM-=, M-aM-=M-& M-aM-<M-^DM-NM-=M-NM-4M-OM-^AM-NM-5M-OM-^B M-aM->M-?M-NM-^QM-NM-8M-NM-7M-NM-=M-NM-1M-aM-?M-^VM-NM-?M-NM-9,

Thai (UCS Level 2):

  Excerpt from a poetry on The Romance of The Three Kingdoms (a Chinese
  classic 'San Gua'):

Runes:

  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+

  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.



Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its

ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to

decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a



CAT
systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random


outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
decisions on the basis of data. textbook
Statistical
methods are
used in almost every
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
biology, business, communications, economics,
        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of


statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics$
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most$
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and$
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from$
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to$
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary$
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.$
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.$

In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce$
data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.$
$
$
$
Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific$
study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its$
$
ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into$
information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to$
$
decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a$
$
$
$
CAT$
systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in$
the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of$
the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random$
$
$
outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable$
decisions on the basis of data. textbook$
Statistical$
methods are$
used in almost every$
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,$
biology, business, communications, economics,$
        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,$
    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and$
        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological$
intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to$
        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that$
prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of$
        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes$
in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,$
summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics$
methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of$
$
$
statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental$
data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude$
whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic$
steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate$
statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we$
properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the$
question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to$
proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.$

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

  â•‘â””â”€â•¥â”€â”˜â•‘  â”‚â•šâ•â•¤â•â•â”‚  â”‚â•˜â•â•ªâ•â•›â”‚  â”‚â•™â”€â•€â”€â•œâ”‚  â”ƒâ””â”€â•‚â”€â”˜â”ƒ  â–‘â–‘â–’â–’â–“â–“â–ˆâ–ˆ â”Š  â”† â•Ž â•  â”‡ â”‹ â–
  â•šâ•â•â•©â•â•â•  â””â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”˜  â•°â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â•¯  â•°â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â•¯  â”—â”â”â”»â”â”â”›           â””â•Œâ•Œâ”˜ â•Ž â”—â•â•â”› â”‹  â–â–‚â–ƒâ–„â–…â–†â–‡â–ˆ
In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.



Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its

ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to

decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a



CAT
systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random


outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
decisions on the basis of data. textbook
Statistical
methods are
used in almost every
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
biology, business, communications, economics,
        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of


statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.

    1	This textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
     2	and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
     3	books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
     4	then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
     5	various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
     6	introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
     7	applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
     8	We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

   131	In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
   132	data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.



   133	Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
   134	study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its

   135	ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
   136	information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to

   137	decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a



   138	CAT
   139	systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
   140	the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
   141	the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random


   142	outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
   143	decisions on the basis of data. textbook
   144	Statistical
   145	methods are
   146	used in almost every
   147	discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
   148	biology, business, communications, economics,
   149	        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
   150	    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
   151	        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
   152	intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
   153	        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
   154	prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
   155	        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
   156	in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
   157	summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
   158	methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of


   159	statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
   160	data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
   161	whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
   162	steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
   163	statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
   164	properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
   165	question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
   166	proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.

    1	This textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
     2	and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
     3	books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
     4	then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
     5	various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
     6	introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
     7	applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
     8	We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

   118	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said
   119	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')

   165	  â•šâ•â•â•©â•â•â•  â””â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”˜  â•°â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â•¯  â•°â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â•¯  â”—â”â”â”»â”â”â”›           â””â•Œâ•Œâ”˜ â•Ž â”—â•â•â”› â”‹  â–â–‚â–ƒâ–„â–…â–†â–‡â–ˆ
   166	In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
   167	data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.
   168	
   169	
   170	
   171	Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
   172	study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its
   173	
   174	ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
   175	information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to
   176	
   177	decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a
   178	
   179	
   180	
   181	CAT
   182	systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
   183	the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
   184	the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random
   185	
   186	
   187	outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
   188	decisions on the basis of data. textbook
   189	Statistical
   190	methods are
   191	used in almost every
   192	discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
   193	biology, business, communications, economics,
   194	        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
   195	    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
   196	        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
   197	intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
   198	        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
   199	prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
   200	        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
   201	in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
   202	summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
   203	methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of
   204	
   205	
   206	statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
   207	data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
   208	whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
   209	steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
   210	statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
   211	properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
   212	question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
   213	proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.

his textbook provides a calculus-based coverage of statistics textbook and introduces students to methods of theoretical statistics
and their applications. It assumes no prior knowledge of statistics or probability theory, but does require calculus. Most
books at this level are written with elaborate coverage of probability. textbook This requires teaching one semester of probability and
then continuing with one or two semesters of statistics. This creates a particular problem for nonstatistics majors from
various disciplines who want to obtain a sound TEXTBOOK background in mathematical statistics and applications. It is our aim to
introduce basic concepts of statistics with sound theoretical explanations. Because statistics is basically an interdisciplinary
applied subject, we offer many applied examples and textbook relevant exercises from different areas. Knowledge of using computers for data analysis is desirable.
We present examples of solving statistical problems using Minitab, SPSS, and SAS.

  â•‘â””â”€â•¥â”€â”˜â•‘  â”‚â•šâ•â•¤â•â•â”‚  â”‚â•˜â•â•ªâ•â•›â”‚  â”‚â•™â”€â•€â”€â•œâ”‚  â”ƒâ””â”€â•‚â”€â”˜â”ƒ  â–‘â–‘â–’â–’â–“â–“â–ˆâ–ˆ â”Š  â”† â•Ž â•  â”‡ â”‹ â–
  â•šâ•â•â•©â•â•â•  â””â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â”˜  â•°â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â•¯  â•°â”€â”€â”´â”€â”€â•¯  â”—â”â”â”»â”â”â”›           â””â•Œâ•Œâ”˜ â•Ž â”—â•â•â”› â”‹  â–â–‚â–ƒâ–„â–…â–†â–‡â–ˆ
In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce
data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.

Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific
study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its

ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into
information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to

decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a

CAT
systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in
the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of
the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random

outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable
decisions on the basis of data. textbook
Statistical
methods are
used in almost every
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,
biology, business, communications, economics,
        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,
    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and
        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological
intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to
        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that
prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of
        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes
in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,
summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics
methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of

statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental
data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude
whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic
steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate
statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we
properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the
question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to
proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.
123			11 /_______________________________________________/\0
124 Statistical
methods are

used in almost every
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,

 		Qbiology, business, communications, economics,
 			Qbiology, business,
 	12345 12345,

    M-`M-9M-^O M-`M-9M-^AM-`M-8M-^\M-`M-9M-^HM-`M-8M-^YM-`M-8M-^TM-`M-8M-4M-`M-8M-^YM-`M-8M-.M-`M-8M-1M-`M-9M-^HM-`M-8M-^YM-`M-9M-^@M-`M-8M-*M-`M-8M-7M-`M-9M-^HM-`M-8M--M-`M-8M-!M-`M-9M-^BM-`M-8M-^WM-`M-8M-#M-`M-8M-!M-`M-9M-^AM-`M-8M-*M-`M-8M-^YM-`M-8M-*M-`M-8M-1M-`M-8M-^GM-`M-9M-^@M-`M-8M-'M-`M-8M-^J  M-`M-8M-^^M-`M-8M-#M-`M-8M-0M-`M-8M-^[M-`M-8M-^AM-`M-9M-^@M-`M-8M-^AM-`M-8M-(M-`M-8M-^AM-`M-8M--M-`M-8M-^GM-`M-8M-^ZM-`M-8M-9M-`M-9M-^JM-`M-8M-^AM-`M-8M-9M-`M-9M-^IM-`M-8M-^BM-`M-8M-6M-`M-9M-^IM-`M-8M-^YM-`M-9M-^CM-`M-8M-+M-`M-8M-!M-`M-9M-^H$

$
  M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-3M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^O M-aM-^ZM-;M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^[M-^RM-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-> M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-+M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^[M-^ZM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^[M-^V M-aM-^ZM->M-aM-^ZM-)M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^ZM-*M-aM-^ZM-1M-aM-^[M-^^M-aM-^ZM-"M-aM-^[M-^W M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^AM-aM-^ZM-& M-aM-^ZM-&M-aM-^ZM-* M-aM-^ZM-9M-aM-^[M-^VM-aM-^[M-%M-aM-^ZM-+$
$
  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$
$

  M-bM-^UM-^ZM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-)M-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^]  M-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^X  M-bM-^UM-0M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-/  M-bM-^UM-0M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-/  M-bM-^TM-^WM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-;M-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^[           M-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^UM-^LM-bM-^UM-^LM-bM-^TM-^X M-bM-^UM-^N M-bM-^TM-^WM-bM-^UM-^MM-bM-^UM-^MM-bM-^TM-^[ M-bM-^TM-^K  M-bM-^VM-^AM-bM-^VM-^BM-bM-^VM-^CM-bM-^VM-^DM-bM-^VM-^EM-bM-^VM-^FM-bM-^VM-^GM-bM-^VM-^H$
In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce$
data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.$
$
$
$
Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific$
study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its$
$
ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into$
information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to$
$
decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a$
$
$
$
CAT$
systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in$
the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of$
the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random$
$
$
outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable$
decisions on the basis of data. textbook$
Statistical$
methods are$
used in almost every$
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,$
biology, business, communications, economics,$
        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,$
    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and$
        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological$
intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to$
        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that$
prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of$
        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes$
in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,$
summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics$
methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of$
$
$
statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental$
data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude$
whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic$
steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate$
statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we$
properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the$
question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to$
proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.$

methods are$
$

used in almost every$
discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,$
$

    50	  M-PM-^WM-PM-0M-QM-^@M-PM-5M-PM-3M-PM-8M-QM-^AM-QM-^BM-QM-^@M-PM-8M-QM-^@M-QM-^CM-PM-9M-QM-^BM-PM-5M-QM-^AM-QM-^L M-QM-^AM-PM-5M-PM-9M-QM-^GM-PM-0M-QM-^A M-PM-=M-PM-0 M-PM-^TM-PM-5M-QM-^AM-QM-^OM-QM-^BM-QM-^CM-QM-^N M-PM-^\M-PM-5M-PM-6M-PM-4M-QM-^CM-PM-=M-PM-0M-QM-^@M-PM->M-PM-4M-PM-=M-QM-^CM-QM-^N M-PM-^ZM-PM->M-PM-=M-QM-^DM-PM-5M-QM-^@M-PM-5M-PM-=M-QM-^FM-PM-8M-QM-^N M-PM-?M-PM->$

    52	  M-PM-^ZM-PM->M-PM-=M-QM-^DM-PM-5M-QM-^@M-PM-5M-PM-=M-QM-^FM-PM-8M-QM-^O M-QM-^AM-PM->M-PM-1M-PM-5M-QM-^@M-PM-5M-QM-^B M-QM-^HM-PM-8M-QM-^@M-PM->M-PM-:M-PM-8M-PM-9 M-PM-:M-QM-^@M-QM-^CM-PM-3 M-QM-^MM-PM-:M-QM-^AM-PM-?M-PM-5M-QM-^@M-QM-^BM-PM->M-PM-2 M-PM-?M-PM->  M-PM-2M-PM->M-PM-?M-QM-^@M-PM->M-QM-^AM-PM-0M-PM-< M-PM-3M-PM-;M-PM->M-PM-1M-PM-0M-PM-;M-QM-^LM-PM-=M-PM->M-PM-3M-PM->$
    53	  M-PM-^XM-PM-=M-QM-^BM-PM-5M-QM-^@M-PM-=M-PM-5M-QM-^BM-PM-0 M-PM-8 Unicode, M-PM-;M-PM->M-PM-:M-PM-0M-PM-;M-PM-8M-PM-7M-PM-0M-QM-^FM-PM-8M-PM-8 M-PM-8 M-PM-8M-PM-=M-QM-^BM-PM-5M-QM-^@M-PM-=M-PM-0M-QM-^FM-PM-8M-PM->M-PM-=M-PM-0M-PM-;M-PM-8M-PM-7M-PM-0M-QM-^FM-PM-8M-PM-8, M-PM-2M-PM->M-PM-?M-PM-;M-PM->M-QM-^IM-PM-5M-PM-=M-PM-8M-QM-^N M-PM-8$
    54	  M-PM-?M-QM-^@M-PM-8M-PM-<M-PM-5M-PM-=M-PM-5M-PM-=M-PM-8M-QM-^N Unicode M-PM-2 M-QM-^@M-PM-0M-PM-7M-PM-;M-PM-8M-QM-^GM-PM-=M-QM-^KM-QM-^E M-PM->M-PM-?M-PM-5M-QM-^@M-PM-0M-QM-^FM-PM-8M-PM->M-PM-=M-PM-=M-QM-^KM-QM-^E M-QM-^AM-PM-8M-QM-^AM-QM-^BM-PM-5M-PM-<M-PM-0M-QM-^E M-PM-8 M-PM-?M-QM-^@M-PM->M-PM-3M-QM-^@M-PM-0M-PM-<M-PM-<M-PM-=M-QM-^KM-QM-^E$

    93	  (Old English, which transcribed into Latin reads 'He cwaeth that he$
    94	  bude thaem lande northweardum with tha Westsae.' and means 'He said$
    95	  that he lived in the northern land near the Western Sea.')$

   124	  M-bM-^UM-^TM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-&M-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^W  M-bM-^TM-^LM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-,M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^P  M-bM-^UM--M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-,M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-.    129	  M-bM-^UM-^QM-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-%M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^XM-bM-^UM-^Q  M-bM-^TM-^BM-bM-^UM-^ZM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-$M-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^]M-bM-^TM-^B  M-bM-^TM-^BM-bM-^UM-^XM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-*M-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^[M-bM-^TM-^B  M-bM-^TM-^BM-bM-^UM-^YM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-^\M-bM-^TM-^B  M-bM-^TM-^CM-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-^BM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^XM-bM-^TM-^C  M-bM-^VM-^QM-bM-^VM-^QM-bM-^VM-^RM-bM-^VM-^RM-bM-^VM-^SM-bM-^VM-^SM-bM-^VM-^HM-bM-^VM-^H M-bM-^TM-^J  M-bM-^TM-^F M-bM-^UM-^N M-bM-^UM-^O  M-bM-^TM-^G M-bM-^TM-^K M-bM-^VM-^O$
   130	  M-bM-^UM-^ZM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-)M-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^PM-bM-^UM-^]  M-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^X  M-bM-^UM-0M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-/  M-bM-^UM-0M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-4M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^TM-^@M-bM-^UM-/  M-bM-^TM-^WM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-;M-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^AM-bM-^TM-^[           M-bM-^TM-^TM-bM-^UM-^LM-bM-^UM-^LM-bM-^TM-^X M-bM-^UM-^N M-bM-^TM-^WM-bM-^UM-^MM-bM-^UM-^MM-bM-^TM-^[ M-bM-^TM-^K  M-bM-^VM-^AM-bM-^VM-^BM-bM-^VM-^CM-bM-^VM-^DM-bM-^VM-^EM-bM-^VM-^FM-bM-^VM-^GM-bM-^VM-^H$
   131	In today's society, decisions are made on the basis of data. Most scientific or industrial studies and experiments produce$
   132	data, and the analysis of these data and drawing useful conclusions from them have become one of the central issues.$
$
   133	Statistics is an integral part of the cat quantitative approach to knowledge. The field of statistics is concerned with the scientific$
   134	study of collecting, organizing, analyzing, and drawing conclusions from data. Statistics benefits all of us because of its$
$
   135	ability to predict the future based on data we have previously gathered. Statistical CAT methods help us to transform data into$
   136	information and knowledge. Statistical concepts enable cat us to solve problems in a diversity of contexts, add substance to$
$
   137	decisions, and reduce guesswork. The discipline textbook of statistics stemmed from the need to place cat knowledge management on a$
$
   138	CAT$
   139	systematic evidence base. TEXTBOOK Earlier works on statistics dealt only with the collection, organization, and presentation of data in$
   140	the form cat of tables and charts. In order to place CAT statistical textbook knowledge on a systematic evidence base, we require a study of$
   141	the laws of CAT probability. In mathematical TEXTBOOK statistics we create a probabilistic model cat and view the data as a set of random$
$
   142	outcomes from that model. TEXTBOOK Advances in probability theory enable us to draw valid conclusions and to make reasonable$
   143	decisions on the basis of data. textbook$
   144	Statistical$
   145	methods are$
   146	used in almost every$
   147	discipline, including agriculture, astronomy,$
   148	biology, business, communications, economics,$
   149	        education, electronics, geology, health sciences, and many other fields of science and engineering,$
   150	    and can aid us in several ways. Modern applications of statistical techniques include statistical communication theory and$
   151	        signal processing, information theory, network security and denial-of-service problems, clinical trials, artificial and biological$
   152	intelligence, quality control of manufactured items, software reliability, and survival analysis. The first of these is to$
   153	        assist us in designing experiments and surveys. We desire our experiment to yield adequate answers to the questions that$
   154	prompted the experiment or survey. We would like the answers to have good precision without involving a lot of$
   155	        expenditure. Statistically designed experiments facilitate the development of robust products that are insensitive to changes$
   156	in the environment and internal component variation. Another way that statistics assists us is in organizing, describing,$
   157	summarizing, and displaying experimental data. This is termed descriptive statistics. Many of the descriptive statistics$
   158	methods presented in this chapter are also part of the general area known as exploratory data analysis (EDA). A third use of$
$
   159	statistics is in drawing inferences and making decisions based on data. For example, scientists may collect experimental$
   160	data to prove or disprove an intuitive conjecture or hypothesis. Through the proper use of statistics, we can conclude$
   161	whether the hypothesis is valid or not. In the process of solving a real-life problem using statistics, the following three basic$
   162	steps may be identified. First, consistent with the objective of the problem, we identify the model using the appropriate$
   163	statistical method. Then, we justify the applicability of the selected model to fulfill the aim of our problem. Last, we$
   164	properly apply the related model to analyze the data and make the necessary decisions, which results in answering the$
   165	question of our problem with minimum risk. Starting with Chapter 2, we will study the necessary background material to$
   166	proceed with the development of statistical methods for solving real-world problems.$
